'Zhejiang' (}}), formerly romanized as 'Chekiang', is an eastern coastal
province of the People's Republic of China. The word Zhejiang means zigzagging
river and was the old name of the Qiantang River,
[http://www.people.com.cn/GB/shenghuo/1090/2435218.html Origin of the Names of
China's Provinces], People's Daily Online. which passes through Hangzhou,
the provincial capital. The name of the province is often abbreviated to its
first character, "æµ".

Zhejiang borders Jiangsu province and Shanghai municipality to the north, Anhui
province to the northwest, Jiangxi province to the west, and Fujian province to
the south; to the east is the East China Sea, beyond which lie the Ryukyu
Islands of Japan.
